    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Window sills that consist of a stone slab as long as the window is wide and that fit into the walls between the jambs; distinguished from "lug sills" which are longer than the width of the window opening and are let into the wall on each side.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000033931/Putnam and Carlson, Architectural and Building Trades Dictionary (1974)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Wordt gebruikt voor vensterbanken die bestaan uit een stenen plaat die even lang is als de breedte van het raam, en die tussen de  stijlen in de muren passen. Te onderscheiden van 'lug sills' die langer zijn dan de breedte van het raam en die aan weerszijden in de muur zijn geplaatst.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>與窗戶等距的窗臺，由嵌入兩側邊框之間牆面的石板所構成。與「凸耳窗臺」不同，凸耳窗臺的長度大於窗戶開口寬度，兩端分別嵌入牆中。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
